post_text: As educators in the urban community, it is our civil duty to speak out, speak up, and speak against the social injustices that have plagued our nation for far too long. This is a time to educate our children and future generations on what it means to be a person of color in America, and what they can do to change the narrative surrounding our culture and communities. It's ironic that we live in a world where those that have sworn to "serve and protect" are the very hands at which our black brothers and sisters dying. Silence is not an option, we must stand up and take action against these injustices. Our hearts are beyond heavy right now for the families that have suffered these losses. We've decided to stand in solidarity with them, will you???

Hey there Eagle families! Our 8th grade Graduation Ceremony is just 8 days away! As we move closer to the big day, we would like to issue a few friendly reminders:

- Remember to wear your masks
- Please stay in your vehicles, the Deans will deliver the certificates to you
- If you wish to have your scholar's photo taken, a staff member will safely coordinate the photo near your vehicle
- Please be respectful during the announcement of graduates, so families can hear their scholar's name announced
- Once the ceremony concludes, our staff will promptly and safely direct all vehicles to the exit

Note: The ceremony will start promptly at 1pm, so please be on time to hear your scholar's name and celebrate their achievement!

post_text:
3D Shapes

You may have heard of 3-D movies. You may have even seen one. The D in 3-D stands for dimensional. A dimension is a direction that something can be measured. Flat things can be measured in two ways. They can be measured by length and by width. Thatâ€™s why flat things are sometimes called 2-D or two-dimensional. Three-dimensional things can be measured in three ways. They can be measured by length and width like flat things. They can also be measured by their height. Height is what lets them come up off the paper or the screen.Three-dimensional shapes in math are called solids.

1. What is a dimension?

2. How can flat, two-dimensional things be measured?

3. What are three-dimensional shapes called in math?

post_text:
Math Problem of the Day!

Sam the Squirrel found a basket of pine cones one morning. He decided that every day he would double the number of pine cones in the basket in the morning and eat 2 pine cones out of the basket in the afternoon. At the end of the third day, there were 34 pine cones in the basket. How many pine cones were in the basket when Sam the Squirrel found it? Hint! Work backwards from the 3rd day :)
text:
Math Problem of the Day!

Sam the Squirrel found a basket of pine cones one morning. He decided that every day he would double the number of pine cones in the basket in the morning and eat 2 pine cones out of the basket in the afternoon. At the end of the third day, there were 34 pine cones in the basket. How many pine cones were in the basket when Sam the Squirrel found it? Hint! Work backwards from the 3rd day :)

Math Problem of the Day

4th Grade - 4.OA.4

1. There are 56 fourth graders going on a field trip. The teacher wants to divide them evenly into groups of at least 4 students and no more than 8 students. What are the ways to divide the students evenly into groups?

2. The factors of 6 are also the factors of which number?
A. 5
B. 20
C. 10
D. 30

Mike chose D as the correct answer. How did he get that answer?

3. Which sentence(s) below are true about the numbers 1, 3, and 9? Circle the letter for all that apply.

A. Adding 1 to any of the numbers will make a composite number.
B. Adding 2 to any of the numbers will make a prime number.
C. 3 and 9 are prime numbers.
D. All the numbers are factors of 9.
E. All the numbers are factors of any multiple of 3.

post_text:
Math Problem of the Day!

2nd Grade - 2.OA.1

1. Will has 8 stickers. He gives 2 to Sara. Then he puts some on his lunch bag. He has 4 stickers left. How many does he put on his lunch bag?
A. 2
B. 6
C. 4
D. 10

Sam chose D. This answer is wrong. How did Sam get her answer?

2. Sal has 8 balloons. He has 3 red balloons. The rest are blue. Kay has 5 more blue balloons than Sal. How many blue balloons does Kay have?
A. 5
B. 8
C. 10
D. 16

3. Choose a number sentence.
3 + 8 = 11
2 + 5 = 7
15 - 6 = 9
9 - 4 = 5

Write a two-step word problem. Your number sentence must be used to solve one of the steps.
text:
Math Problem of the Day!

2nd Grade - 2.OA.1

1. Will has 8 stickers. He gives 2 to Sara. Then he puts some on his lunch bag. He has 4 stickers left. How many does he put on his lunch bag?
A. 2
B. 6
C. 4
D. 10

Sam chose D. This answer is wrong. How did Sam get her answer?

2. Sal has 8 balloons. He has 3 red balloons. The rest are blue. Kay has 5 more blue balloons than Sal. How many blue balloons does Kay have?
A. 5
B. 8
C. 10
D. 16

3. Choose a number sentence.
3 + 8 = 11
2 + 5 = 7
15 - 6 = 9
9 - 4 = 5

Write a two-step word problem. Your number sentence must be used to solve one of the steps.

post_text:
Math Problem of the Day!

We are now getting into our two week extended break, so expect some more problems and readings every day! Be on the lookout for some extra posts in the next few days. The teachers & staff at Euclid Prep are missing their kids, classrooms, and teaching. Remember to comment correct answers for shout outs daily! Stay safe Eagle Family!
-Mrs. Tirabassi

3rd Grade Math - 3.MD.1

1. The Mendoza family left home at 10:30. They drove 25 minutes and stopped at the store. The family spent 20 minutes in the store. Then they drove another 13 minutes to get to the beach. What time did they get to the beach?

2. Sharna leaves school at 3:10. It takes 12 minutes for her to walk home from school. It takes 7 minutes for her to gather her soccer equipment and 10 more minutes to get to the soccer field. Soccer practice starts at 3:45. Sharna thinks she will be late. Do you agree? Explain.

3. A movie starts at 5:15. Rudy wants to get to the theater 25 minutes before the movie starts. It takes 10 minutes to drive to the theater. What time should Rudy leave home?

post_text:
Math Problem of the Day! Comment answers correctly for a shout-out tomorrow!

Reading and math problems of the day are designed to help our families prepare for the Reading requirements as laid out in our state standards. They are created to prompt collaborative discussions between you and your scholar, and help ease the dreaded "brain drain"! We will post reading and/or math daily. Stay safe! - Mrs. Tirabassi

6th Grade Math - 6.EE.3

1. Which expression is equivalent to 6 + 7n + 4 + 8n? Select all that apply.
A. 13n + 12n
B. 5(3n + 2)
C. 5(3n + 10)
D. 15n + 10

2. Larry bought 12 containers of pasta salad for a school picnic. Each container held the same number of ounces of salad. Students finished the pasta salad in 8 of
the containers.

a. Let p equal the number of ounces of pasta salad in one container. Write an expression with two terms to represent how many ounces of pasta salad are left.

b. Simplify the expression you wrote in the problem above to create an equivalent expression. Use the distributive property.

post_text:
Math Problem of the Day! Comment answers correctly for a shout-out tomorrow!

Reading and math problems of the day are designed to help our families prepare for the Reading requirements as laid out in our state standards. They are created to prompt collaborative discussions between you and your scholar, and help ease the dreaded "brain drain"! We will post reading and/or math daily. Stay safe! - Mrs. Tirabassi

Grade 2 Math - 2.OA.1

1. Sarah has 13 marbles. 4 marbles are blue, the rest are white. How many white marbles are there?
A. 13-4 = _______
B. 13-______ = 4
C. 13+4 = ______
D. 4+_____ = 13

2. There are 5 cows in the barn. There are 8 fewer cows in the barn than the field. How many cows are in the field?
A. 3
B. 8
C. 12
D. 13

3. Jen has 9 markers. She has 5 more markers than pencils. How many pencils does Jen have?

Say yes or no if each equation can be used to solve the problem or not.

A. 9-5 = 4
B. 9+5 = 14
C. 14-9 = 5
D. 5+4 = 9

post_text:
I can barely contain my excitement over the FANTASTIC School & Community Thanksgiving Feast hosted by the
Euclid Preparatory Team â€“ one of our brand new schools! Last nightâ€™s event was one for the records.

This incredible school rose to the occasion as a family for a time
of support and celebration of our parents and scholars. The EPS Team hosted a potluck dinner with the
participation of a majority of staff and families, and had an amazing turnout as follows:
- More than 60 parents/grandparents
- Countless students
- Mayor of Euclid
- 2 Councilpersons
- Fox 8 News Cameraman
- The entire EPS Team!

KUDOS Principal Montague, Dean Fishback, and the entire Euclid Prep team for an occasion to remember!
